00:00:09.790 --> 00:00:09.848
Thank you.

00:00:10.732 --> 00:00:11.690
So it's great to be
back at the RI again.

00:00:12.440 --> 00:00:16.373
I spoke here last year and it's
such a fantastic auditorium.

00:00:17.001 --> 00:00:18.435
I'm a professor of astrophysics
at the University of Sydney,

00:00:19.500 --> 00:00:22.966
and as was mentioned there,
I'm a cosmologist, right.

00:00:23.780 --> 00:00:24.686
My job is to try and
understand the forces that

00:00:25.940 --> 00:00:26.513
have shaped the evolution
of the Universe,

00:00:28.100 --> 00:00:28.890
from a time when the
Universe was basically

00:00:30.110 --> 00:00:30.590
formless to the rich
structure of the Universe

00:00:32.630 --> 00:00:34.496
that we see around us today.

00:00:34.729 --> 00:00:35.888
So what I want to do
tonight is basically take us

00:00:36.770 --> 00:00:38.503
all in a bit of a journey.

00:00:38.560 --> 00:00:39.140
What we want to do
is not take a journey

00:00:40.580 --> 00:00:40.906
through space but a
journey through time.

00:00:42.920 --> 00:00:43.313
And we want to look
backwards first to see

00:00:45.260 --> 00:00:45.530
how our Universe evolved from
its birth in the Big Bang

00:00:48.590 --> 00:00:52.523
to the Universe with stars, and
planets, and galaxies today.

00:00:52.610 --> 00:00:53.033
And then we want to turn around
and run the Universe forward

00:00:56.120 --> 00:00:58.786
and ask what fate
holds for the Universe.

00:00:59.060 --> 00:01:00.016
Just what is going to
happen as this Universe gets

00:01:01.370 --> 00:01:02.436
older and older?

00:01:03.790 --> 00:01:06.590
So every journey starts
with a single step,

00:01:06.920 --> 00:01:08.013
and before we take a step
backwards into the past or step

00:01:09.560 --> 00:01:10.133
forwards into the
future, I think

00:01:11.120 --> 00:01:11.483
it's important to
understand where we are,

00:01:13.490 --> 00:01:13.886
where we are today.

00:01:14.360 --> 00:01:17.026
Just what kind of
Universe do we live in?

00:01:17.249 --> 00:01:18.258
And, of course, the
starting point for that

00:01:19.040 --> 00:01:20.373
is where are we now?

00:01:20.720 --> 00:01:23.053
And we find ourselves
on the surface

00:01:24.930 --> 00:01:26.596
of a small, rocky planet.

00:01:27.300 --> 00:01:27.806
And it's a very special planet.

00:01:28.860 --> 00:01:29.546
It's an extraordinary
planet, because out

00:01:30.840 --> 00:01:31.103
of the thousands
of planets we know,

00:01:32.910 --> 00:01:33.336
that we've discovered
in the Universe,

00:01:34.950 --> 00:01:35.778
and the trillions
of planets we think

00:01:36.522 --> 00:01:37.480
are out there in the
observable Universe,

00:01:38.230 --> 00:01:40.430
this is the only
one where we have

00:01:41.490 --> 00:01:42.106
complete and utter evidence that
there is life on this planet.

00:01:44.940 --> 00:01:46.163
Sometimes it's a bit difficult
to see intelligent life

00:01:47.250 --> 00:01:47.400
on this planet, but there
is life on this planet.

00:01:50.300 --> 00:01:50.450
OK.

00:01:51.150 --> 00:01:51.650
Now, I'm going to touch
upon life in the Universe

00:01:53.850 --> 00:01:54.783
as we go out into the
future a little bit.

00:01:55.650 --> 00:01:55.963
So it's important to
try and understand

00:01:57.870 --> 00:01:59.870
what we mean when we say life.

00:02:00.750 --> 00:02:04.683
And it turns out that defining
life is incredibly difficult.

00:02:05.590 --> 00:02:08.723
When you get down to the
details, how you define

00:02:09.600 --> 00:02:12.000
whether what's alive
and what's dead,

00:02:12.810 --> 00:02:13.913
people set up rules and say,
this is my dividing line.

00:02:15.240 --> 00:02:16.123
This is the living stuff,
that's the dead stuff.

00:02:17.490 --> 00:02:18.490
Or this stuff on the dead side,
which just looks a bit alive.

00:02:20.490 --> 00:02:20.690
And that happens all the time.

00:02:22.290 --> 00:02:23.436
And there are arguments about
whether viruses are alive.

00:02:24.810 --> 00:02:25.350
Or the prions are
alive, these things

00:02:26.670 --> 00:02:28.403
even smaller than viruses.

00:02:28.440 --> 00:02:28.721
And so defining life, that
would take another lecture

00:02:31.625 --> 00:02:32.383
and probably a
few more lectures,

00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:33.883
and we would be here until
almost the end of the Universe

00:02:35.850 --> 00:02:37.850
trying to define what life is.

00:02:38.250 --> 00:02:39.396
But what I'm going to touch
upon is an aspect of life

00:02:40.570 --> 00:02:44.103
which, in my opinion, I think
is one of the key things

00:02:44.370 --> 00:02:44.870
that life does if we're
going to define something

00:02:47.070 --> 00:02:48.470
as a living organism.

00:02:49.450 --> 00:02:51.383
And that's to do with energy.

00:02:52.170 --> 00:02:53.903
All life processes energy.

00:02:55.870 --> 00:02:56.450
So what we have in
this picture here,

00:02:57.690 --> 00:02:59.490
we have a lovely sunflower.

00:02:59.510 --> 00:03:01.910
That sunflower has
captured sunlight,

00:03:02.100 --> 00:03:03.040
and that sunlight has
been stored as energy

00:03:03.960 --> 00:03:06.493
in the chemical bonds
inside the plant.

00:03:07.120 --> 00:03:09.986
Creatures come along
and they eat the plant,

00:03:10.120 --> 00:03:10.923
and they can use that energy
to run their own chemical

00:03:12.850 --> 00:03:14.450
processes in their body.

00:03:15.156 --> 00:03:16.065
And, similarly, we
could eat the plants

00:03:16.780 --> 00:03:17.914
or we could eat the animals
that ate the plants.

00:03:18.779 --> 00:03:19.264
And so there's just a
continuous progression

00:03:21.160 --> 00:03:23.360
whereby we use and
process energy,

00:03:24.190 --> 00:03:25.036
and that is one of the defining
characteristics of life.

00:03:27.010 --> 00:03:29.543
All life processes
energy of some sort.

00:03:29.950 --> 00:03:33.483
And that energy not only
drives the chemical reactions

00:03:33.490 --> 00:03:37.490
in your body, but it also drives
the sort of mental reactions

00:03:38.290 --> 00:03:38.717
in your mind when
you think, right.

00:03:40.129 --> 00:03:41.138
We all know that when
you have a sugar low,

00:03:41.920 --> 00:03:42.653
it's very hard to
think about anything.

00:03:43.720 --> 00:03:44.200
You need energy
to run your brain.

00:03:45.440 --> 00:03:46.303
In fact, it uses up
a very large amount

00:03:47.110 --> 00:03:49.176
of the energy that you take in.

00:03:51.040 --> 00:03:53.506
So there's actually
a very strong link

00:03:53.590 --> 00:03:57.123
between flows of energy and
processing of information.

00:03:59.590 --> 00:04:00.290
And any time you
run your computer

00:04:01.090 --> 00:04:01.380
and your computer is doing
very difficult calculations,

00:04:04.400 --> 00:04:04.426
or updating Facebook,
or something,

00:04:06.640 --> 00:04:07.053
it's processing
information, and you

00:04:08.560 --> 00:04:08.853
can feel the heat that's
generated by that information

00:04:11.800 --> 00:04:12.866
being processed.

00:04:13.610 --> 00:04:13.850
So if any living creature is
going to be sentient and know

00:04:17.170 --> 00:04:19.770
about its environment
and react to that,

00:04:20.029 --> 00:04:20.341
it's going to need to have an
energy flow to drive that sort

00:04:23.650 --> 00:04:24.650
of behaviour.

00:04:26.200 --> 00:04:26.613
Now, the ultimate source of
energy on the Earth of course

00:04:29.520 --> 00:04:30.520
is the Sun.

00:04:31.780 --> 00:04:32.236
In the middle of the Sun,
every second 11 million tonnes

00:04:34.990 --> 00:04:37.256
of hydrogen get
turned into helium.

00:04:37.270 --> 00:04:37.726
That releases energy,
which takes 100,000 years

00:04:39.880 --> 00:04:40.019
to percolate through the
Sun, and then 8 minutes

00:04:42.874 --> 00:04:43.658
to get from the
surface of the Sun

00:04:44.290 --> 00:04:47.690
to the Earth, where it's
absorbed by this sunflower,

00:04:47.950 --> 00:04:48.363
or it lands on the
pavement outside in London

00:04:50.470 --> 00:04:52.603
and makes the place even hotter.

00:04:53.560 --> 00:04:56.026
So all life on Earth
exists because we

00:04:56.770 --> 00:04:57.052
have a vast reservoir of
energy right next door to us

00:04:59.954 --> 00:05:00.354
in the Universe.

00:05:00.620 --> 00:05:01.133
And we can use that
energy, and that

00:05:02.440 --> 00:05:06.040
has driven life and evolution
up until the present day.

00:05:07.900 --> 00:05:11.166
Take away that source of
energy, you have no life.

00:05:12.600 --> 00:05:13.126
What we'll be seeing
is that energy

00:05:14.340 --> 00:05:17.340
will come to play a
critical role in what life

00:05:17.640 --> 00:05:18.173
can do when we look at the
far future of the Universe.

00:05:20.640 --> 00:05:22.706
It becomes the scarce resource.

00:05:23.490 --> 00:05:23.793
It's the thing
that any life that

00:05:25.320 --> 00:05:25.500
exists in the distant
future Universe

00:05:27.540 --> 00:05:31.406
is going to need to seek if
it's going to continue to live.

00:05:31.864 --> 00:05:33.248
But let's just try and remember
our place in the Universe.

00:05:34.280 --> 00:05:35.538
As I said, we're on the
surface of this rocky planet.

00:05:36.488 --> 00:05:37.488


00:05:39.500 --> 00:05:39.963
Energy is given to
us by the Sun, which

00:05:41.570 --> 00:05:43.503
is a very typical dwarf star.

00:05:44.630 --> 00:05:44.916
And our Sun is not
alone in the universe,

00:05:47.010 --> 00:05:47.616
but the Sun actually occupies
a small patch of the Universe

00:05:50.270 --> 00:05:53.803
with roughly 300 billion
other suns in an object which

00:05:54.830 --> 00:05:56.563
is known as the Milky Way.

00:05:57.550 --> 00:05:57.926
When we look out
into the Universe,

00:05:59.440 --> 00:06:02.573
we see that there are
possibly a hundred billion

00:06:02.980 --> 00:06:05.513
to a trillion other
galaxies out there.

00:06:06.520 --> 00:06:06.786
So there's a huge number of
stars, huge number of galaxies,

00:06:10.120 --> 00:06:10.290
huge number of potential places
where there could be life.

00:06:13.750 --> 00:06:14.800
But we have no idea what
the frequency of life

00:06:15.700 --> 00:06:15.946
is in the Universe.

00:06:16.720 --> 00:06:20.586
Life could be very common, or
life could be extremely rare.

00:06:21.310 --> 00:06:21.850
And all of our
observational evidence

00:06:23.170 --> 00:06:23.846
is quite consistent
with this being

00:06:24.760 --> 00:06:25.594
the only place in
the Universe where

00:06:26.259 --> 00:06:26.294
there is life at the moment.

00:06:28.090 --> 00:06:30.423
So I said, this is
a special planet.

00:06:31.310 --> 00:06:31.533
So before we play the game
of looking into the future,

00:06:34.620 --> 00:06:34.776
let's work out how we understand
what happened in the past.

00:06:38.330 --> 00:06:39.073
And what we know
is that people have

00:06:39.920 --> 00:06:40.523
looked at the skies
for thousands of years

00:06:42.050 --> 00:06:42.202
and you see patterns
of stars on the sky.

00:06:44.564 --> 00:06:45.348
And people have
generally invented

00:06:45.980 --> 00:06:48.580
stories of heroes,
and gods, and legends

00:06:50.060 --> 00:06:52.926
to explain the various
patterns that we see.

00:06:53.970 --> 00:06:54.483
For us here at
the RI, of course,

00:06:55.590 --> 00:06:56.560
the important thing is
not just the stories

00:06:57.420 --> 00:06:59.620
that people have
told but how they

00:07:00.120 --> 00:07:02.586
came to apply science
to understanding

00:07:02.760 --> 00:07:04.760
the evolution of the Universe.

00:07:05.070 --> 00:07:05.783
And this all
happened, of course,

00:07:06.490 --> 00:07:06.926
during the time of the
birth of modern science.

00:07:09.120 --> 00:07:11.386
And I'll just pop
up this guy here.

00:07:12.017 --> 00:07:13.200
This, of course, is probably
Britain's most famous

00:07:14.100 --> 00:07:14.215
scientist, second famous if
you consider Stephen Hawking

00:07:17.651 --> 00:07:18.152
as well.

00:07:18.150 --> 00:07:20.750
But this is Isaac
Newton, who in my mind

00:07:21.540 --> 00:07:24.273
should be Britain's
most famous scientist.

00:07:24.630 --> 00:07:24.856
Isaac Newton was
around at the time

00:07:26.670 --> 00:07:29.736
when there was just a
changing viewpoint on how

00:07:30.360 --> 00:07:32.160
we understand the Universe.

00:07:32.520 --> 00:07:32.670
And I like this picture.

00:07:33.970 --> 00:07:35.870
This picture was taken off the
back of the old pound note.

00:07:35.870 --> 00:07:37.566
There's people in this
room who clearly have never

00:07:37.440 --> 00:07:37.863
seen an old pound note.

00:07:38.550 --> 00:07:39.200
You're probably too young.

00:07:39.633 --> 00:07:40.682
But in the old days there
used to be a pound note.

00:07:41.850 --> 00:07:42.663
On the back of it was this
picture of Isaac Newton.

00:07:44.370 --> 00:07:44.933
And I like this
picture because it's

00:07:46.140 --> 00:07:49.073
a picture of Isaac Newton
with his telescope.

00:07:49.320 --> 00:07:49.593
And he observed the Universe.

00:07:50.980 --> 00:07:51.716
He used his telescope to
see what was going on.

00:07:53.310 --> 00:07:54.260
Now, he was not the first
to look at the heavens.

00:07:55.560 --> 00:07:55.933
It's reported that Galileo
was the first to look

00:07:58.320 --> 00:07:59.050
at the heavens and see, when he
looked at the planet Jupiter,

00:08:01.590 --> 00:08:01.633
that Jupiter had
companions, that there

00:08:04.080 --> 00:08:05.946
were moons orbiting Jupiter.

00:08:06.990 --> 00:08:09.123
And that led to
this general idea

00:08:09.210 --> 00:08:12.676
that there must be some sort
of order to the heavens,

00:08:12.930 --> 00:08:13.900
and then people wondering
whether the order

00:08:14.760 --> 00:08:18.560
in the heavens is similar to
the order down here on Earth.

00:08:18.570 --> 00:08:18.970
And if I understand how
things behave here on Earth,

00:08:21.570 --> 00:08:22.060
maybe that will
tell me how things

00:08:23.280 --> 00:08:25.146
are behaving in the heavens.

00:08:25.550 --> 00:08:26.240
And so what you
start to do is you

00:08:27.060 --> 00:08:29.926
start to dispel the
need for gods and heroes

00:08:30.840 --> 00:08:31.230
in describing what's
going on in the Universe,

00:08:33.450 --> 00:08:33.454
but what you want are
laws of science that

00:08:36.179 --> 00:08:37.979
tell you how things behave.

00:08:38.344 --> 00:08:39.428
Now, the other reason
that I like this picture

00:08:40.260 --> 00:08:44.393
is that in Newton's lap there is
his book, the Principia, where

00:08:45.300 --> 00:08:45.340
essentially he lay down
the key ideas which

00:08:48.060 --> 00:08:51.660
became classical mechanics,
how things react to forces.

00:08:52.410 --> 00:08:55.743
But also, in there he
described the law of gravity.

00:08:55.890 --> 00:08:57.070
And the picture that we
have in the background there

00:08:58.110 --> 00:09:01.510
is sort of Newton's description
of how gravity works

00:09:01.950 --> 00:09:02.020
in basically holding
the Earth in its orbit

00:09:04.680 --> 00:09:06.613
as it travels around the Sun.

00:09:07.580 --> 00:09:08.320
And, of course, Newton's great
insight was to realise that

00:09:10.640 --> 00:09:14.306
the force that takes an apple
and pulls it from the tree

00:09:14.720 --> 00:09:15.033
and pulls it to the ground is
exactly the same force that

00:09:18.140 --> 00:09:18.223
holds the Moon in its
orbit around the Earth,

00:09:20.990 --> 00:09:21.296
the Earth in its
orbit around the Sun,

00:09:23.150 --> 00:09:26.416
and Jupiter's moons in
their orbit around Jupiter.

00:09:27.230 --> 00:09:30.230
So you could write down
mathematical equations

00:09:30.440 --> 00:09:32.506
and you could make predictions.

00:09:32.686 --> 00:09:33.595
You could predict
where Jupiter's moons

00:09:34.310 --> 00:09:34.680
are going to be
because they are just

00:09:36.340 --> 00:09:38.206
obeying the laws of science.

00:09:38.990 --> 00:09:39.483
No need to introduce any gods
or mythical beings anywhere

00:09:42.230 --> 00:09:42.605
because it's all there
in the equations.

00:09:44.455 --> 00:09:45.213
Now, some people
don't like that.

00:09:45.830 --> 00:09:46.707
That leads to a very
sterile universe of course,

00:09:48.086 --> 00:09:48.845
where everything
is just governed

00:09:49.460 --> 00:09:49.683
by mathematical equations.

00:09:50.970 --> 00:09:51.603
But it at least means
it's predictable.

00:09:52.870 --> 00:09:55.270
We know where things
are going to be.

00:09:55.640 --> 00:09:58.773
Now, in the 400 years or
so since we had Newton,

00:09:59.830 --> 00:10:03.563
the only thing that's changed
is that we've gotten deeper

00:10:03.640 --> 00:10:05.173
into our physical laws.

00:10:05.740 --> 00:10:05.853
We understand the
physical laws that

00:10:07.960 --> 00:10:08.246
govern the Universe
in a lot more detail,

00:10:10.340 --> 00:10:13.406
and we've peered more
deeply into the Universe.

00:10:13.570 --> 00:10:14.656
And what we've done is
developed new telescopes

00:10:15.550 --> 00:10:19.550
that can see further and further
out into the distant cosmos.

00:10:19.860 --> 00:10:20.843
And this picture here,
this is a telescope

00:10:21.610 --> 00:10:22.340
that's currently
being constructed

00:10:23.080 --> 00:10:23.350
in the southern hemisphere.

00:10:24.610 --> 00:10:25.160
This is the Square
Kilometre Array

00:10:26.260 --> 00:10:26.453
which is being built in
South Africa and Australia.

00:10:29.400 --> 00:10:30.156
It will be a radio telescopes,
so it can only see radio waves.

00:10:32.710 --> 00:10:35.443
And it will basically
be a collecting area

00:10:36.190 --> 00:10:37.656
of 1 square Kilometre.

00:10:38.207 --> 00:10:39.540
So we'll be able to see some
of the faintest things that

00:10:40.540 --> 00:10:42.540
are out there in the Universe.

00:10:42.740 --> 00:10:42.848
But, as well as the
Square Kilometre Array,

00:10:45.432 --> 00:10:46.390
we have lots of giant
optical telescopes.

00:10:47.140 --> 00:10:47.473
You have telescopes
in space that

00:10:48.940 --> 00:10:49.493
look at x-rays and
gamma rays, and look

00:10:50.920 --> 00:10:52.586
at microwaves, et cetera.

00:10:52.960 --> 00:10:55.493
And what they've
revealed is a universe

00:10:56.320 --> 00:10:56.690
which is, in my humble
opinion, being a cosmologist,

00:10:59.350 --> 00:11:00.350
quite exciting.

00:11:01.490 --> 00:11:04.156
So what we've got
here, we have a picture

00:11:04.240 --> 00:11:06.640
that was made by
the WMAP consortium.

00:11:07.900 --> 00:11:11.500
WMAP is just a telescope
that's in space, the Wilkinson

00:11:11.710 --> 00:11:13.510
Microwave Anisotropy Probe.

00:11:13.730 --> 00:11:14.270
Its job was to look more
deeply into the universe

00:11:16.390 --> 00:11:18.123
than any other telescopes.

00:11:18.460 --> 00:11:19.446
But what we've got here is a
picture of our entire Universe

00:11:21.340 --> 00:11:24.806
as we understand it, both
in terms of what we can see

00:11:27.010 --> 00:11:27.376
and in terms of what
we can understand

00:11:29.110 --> 00:11:32.776
in terms of the physics that's
going on in the Universe.

00:11:33.200 --> 00:11:36.466
Now, because light travels
at a finite speed, when

00:11:36.620 --> 00:11:37.193
you look at more and
more distant objects,

00:11:38.780 --> 00:11:41.913
you're looking further
and further back in time.

00:11:41.930 --> 00:11:46.063
And what we have is a picture of
our Universe from today as far

00:11:46.760 --> 00:11:47.163
back as we can see,
and what we can see

00:11:48.890 --> 00:11:53.023
is that the Universe has changed
and evolved over its lifetime.

00:11:54.535 --> 00:11:55.893
The first important thing is
to realise that our Universe

00:11:56.910 --> 00:11:58.710
hasn't been around forever.

00:11:59.460 --> 00:12:00.243
The Universe appears to have
been born in an event now known

00:12:02.610 --> 00:12:06.476
as the Big Bang that occurred
roughly 14 billion years ago.

00:12:06.520 --> 00:12:08.653
So our Universe
has a finite age.

00:12:10.650 --> 00:12:10.763
But looking back, we see
that the Universe in the past

00:12:14.070 --> 00:12:16.403
was different to
the Universe today.

00:12:17.460 --> 00:12:21.060
So today around us we see
all these stars and galaxies.

00:12:21.200 --> 00:12:22.263
And as we look back in the past,
we also see stars and galaxies

00:12:24.270 --> 00:12:24.750
but they're different
to the ones today.

00:12:26.390 --> 00:12:27.723
They're less formed.

00:12:28.440 --> 00:12:29.190
And as we push back further
and further, we get to a point

00:12:31.490 --> 00:12:33.823
where there were
no galaxies at all.

00:12:34.476 --> 00:12:35.235
And we can push
back even further

00:12:35.850 --> 00:12:38.916
and we run into the very
start of the Universe.

00:12:39.500 --> 00:12:39.650
So in terms of the
Universe's evolution,

00:12:41.950 --> 00:12:41.970
you can go from left to right.

00:12:43.930 --> 00:12:44.043
At this side, you
have the Big Bang.

00:12:46.150 --> 00:12:46.930
The Universe was
filled with material

00:12:47.770 --> 00:12:49.436
all smoothly distributed.

00:12:49.630 --> 00:12:53.563
Then the laws of physics acted
over roughly 14 billion years

00:12:53.610 --> 00:12:56.343
to give us the Universe
that we see today.

00:12:56.540 --> 00:12:56.546
And so there are a
number of key features

00:12:59.200 --> 00:13:01.266
that people like to talk about.

00:13:01.630 --> 00:13:02.436
The very birth itself,
which is something

00:13:03.490 --> 00:13:03.573
that we do not understand.

00:13:05.140 --> 00:13:05.896
We do not yet have
the laws of physics

00:13:06.850 --> 00:13:07.233
to understand the very
birth of the Universe.

00:13:09.400 --> 00:13:10.113
But after that, the
evolution of the Universe

00:13:11.620 --> 00:13:14.753
through this rapid expansion
known as inflation,

00:13:15.250 --> 00:13:15.310
through the overall evolution of
matter into stars and galaxies,

00:13:19.390 --> 00:13:19.660
that all seems to be
described very accurately

00:13:22.120 --> 00:13:23.653
by the laws of physics.

00:13:24.800 --> 00:13:25.611
So, in fact, one of
the things that we

00:13:26.455 --> 00:13:27.213
like to do-- it's
actually a very

00:13:27.830 --> 00:13:28.163
big part of modern
astrophysics--

00:13:29.630 --> 00:13:32.096
is we like to build
our own universes.

00:13:32.420 --> 00:13:32.816
And I have PhD
students working for me

00:13:34.490 --> 00:13:34.726
that, they generate
universes before breakfast.

00:13:37.320 --> 00:13:37.620
Well, generally not
because none of them

00:13:39.620 --> 00:13:40.283
are ever up before
breakfast, right.

00:13:41.290 --> 00:13:44.356
So early afternoon they'll
generate a universe.

00:13:44.670 --> 00:13:45.233
So what do I mean by that?

00:13:45.840 --> 00:13:46.366
What do I mean by
generate a universe?

00:13:47.780 --> 00:13:48.470
Well, as I said, we think
all of the processes

00:13:50.090 --> 00:13:50.693
underway in the Universe
are just governed

00:13:52.220 --> 00:13:53.753
by the laws of science.

00:13:54.530 --> 00:13:57.930
So if I take my laws of
science, my laws of physics,

00:13:58.280 --> 00:13:58.356
my law of how gravity
works, how gases work,

00:14:01.070 --> 00:14:02.186
how nuclear physics works, et
cetera, et cetera, et cetera,

00:14:03.820 --> 00:14:07.153
and I translate those
equations into computer code,

00:14:08.060 --> 00:14:08.360
and I give the equations
to a computer and say

00:14:10.760 --> 00:14:11.526
to the computer solve
the equations for me--

00:14:12.860 --> 00:14:13.440
because that's what
computers are good at--

00:14:15.080 --> 00:14:18.013
I can actually generate
a synthetic universe.

00:14:18.340 --> 00:14:18.840
And so in the next
sort of animation,

00:14:20.240 --> 00:14:20.260
I'm going to show you
the results of one

00:14:22.820 --> 00:14:25.286
of the big simulations
of the Universe

00:14:25.310 --> 00:14:28.043
that was done by a
group called Illustris.

00:14:28.400 --> 00:14:29.233
Essentially, what
you do is you just

00:14:29.900 --> 00:14:31.109
say I'm going to take a
big volume of the Universe.

00:14:32.024 --> 00:14:32.624
This volume is
billions of light years

00:14:33.890 --> 00:14:34.204
across, much bigger
than our own galaxy.

00:14:36.176 --> 00:14:37.385
I'm going to put matter in
there, nice and smoothly

00:14:38.300 --> 00:14:38.670
distributed like it
was after the Big Bang.

00:14:40.730 --> 00:14:41.323
And then I'm going
to hit Go and you

00:14:42.470 --> 00:14:42.496
can solve all of the
difficult equations,

00:14:45.110 --> 00:14:45.700
and you can tell me what
the Universe looks like.

00:14:47.720 --> 00:14:49.028
So one of the best things
about giving astronomy talks,

00:14:50.012 --> 00:14:51.221
you can just put on the
movies and you can dip out,

00:14:52.136 --> 00:14:52.632
have a cup of coffee.

00:14:53.040 --> 00:14:54.049
Come back when the
movie ends and just say,

00:14:54.831 --> 00:14:56.097
wasn't that lovely?

00:14:56.870 --> 00:14:59.536
So what we're seeing
here, this is matter

00:15:00.260 --> 00:15:00.853
moving in the early Universe.

00:15:01.600 --> 00:15:04.333
So it was originally
smoothly distributed.

00:15:04.550 --> 00:15:07.883
Gravity started acting and
pulling matter together.

00:15:08.240 --> 00:15:09.293
And the matter just doesn't
fall into one big lump,

00:15:10.520 --> 00:15:10.576
but it falls into
several lumps connected

00:15:13.130 --> 00:15:16.463
by this structure which is
known as the cosmic web.

00:15:16.780 --> 00:15:19.513
Inside these lumps,
gas can pool together,

00:15:19.600 --> 00:15:22.400
and when that gas pools,
it can form stars.

00:15:22.420 --> 00:15:22.753
So where you get
these big lumps,

00:15:24.220 --> 00:15:26.553
that's where you
form your galaxies.

00:15:26.810 --> 00:15:27.310
So inside these galaxies
we have stars burning away.

00:15:29.710 --> 00:15:33.576
But stars evolve over time,
and eventually the giant stars,

00:15:33.880 --> 00:15:33.956
they basically run out of
fuel and then they explode.

00:15:37.270 --> 00:15:38.441
And hopefully we should have
an explosion any time now.

00:15:39.699 --> 00:15:40.158
There we are.

00:15:40.240 --> 00:15:41.240
Right on cue.

00:15:42.570 --> 00:15:42.950
What you've got
there is a giant star

00:15:44.590 --> 00:15:45.446
that is being burning elements
in its core-- hydrogen

00:15:47.200 --> 00:15:47.380
to helium, helium
into carbon, carbon

00:15:49.420 --> 00:15:49.556
into oxygen, da da da da.

00:15:50.950 --> 00:15:51.006
All of those elements are caught
up in the heart of the star.

00:15:54.894 --> 00:15:56.278
But for life, having those
elements in the heart of a star

00:15:57.310 --> 00:15:57.793
is pretty pointless.

00:15:58.160 --> 00:15:58.940
What you need them is
spread out through the rest

00:16:00.580 --> 00:16:01.838
of the intergalactic medium--
or interstellar medium,

00:16:02.788 --> 00:16:02.846
I should say--

00:16:03.730 --> 00:16:04.896
and for that material to be
recycled in the next generation

00:16:06.430 --> 00:16:07.430
of stars.

00:16:08.110 --> 00:16:11.376
So that's what happens
when massive stars explode.

00:16:11.980 --> 00:16:12.436
These stars explode and they
spit out the heavy elements

00:16:15.190 --> 00:16:16.856
that are needed for life.

00:16:17.860 --> 00:16:18.483
So it's kind of sobering
to think about this,

00:16:20.170 --> 00:16:23.570
that you look at yourself
and you think, this is me.

00:16:24.190 --> 00:16:26.323
I am [MUMBLES]
years old, but I'm

00:16:28.000 --> 00:16:29.866
made of water, mostly water.

00:16:30.910 --> 00:16:31.446
The hydrogen in that
water, that hydrogen

00:16:33.040 --> 00:16:34.840
was formed in the Big Bang.

00:16:35.020 --> 00:16:37.486
That hydrogen is 14
billion years old.

00:16:38.250 --> 00:16:40.583
The oxygen in the
water, that oxygen

00:16:40.620 --> 00:16:43.086
was formed in the
heart of a big star.

00:16:43.740 --> 00:16:46.473
And, in fact, the
elements that make up me

00:16:46.530 --> 00:16:47.063
have probably been through
the hearts of several stars

00:16:49.530 --> 00:16:50.236
through several generations
of being formed,

00:16:51.690 --> 00:16:54.556
material spat out,
recycled, being spat out,

00:16:54.780 --> 00:16:56.046
and being recycled.

00:16:57.250 --> 00:16:57.996
And the one that I
always like to mention

00:16:59.170 --> 00:17:01.036
is that elements like this--

00:17:01.650 --> 00:17:04.050
I was told by the
jeweller it's gold.

00:17:04.792 --> 00:17:05.792
It might be.

00:17:05.849 --> 00:17:06.849
But gold.

00:17:07.560 --> 00:17:10.160
Stars don't create
gold when stars burn.

00:17:11.640 --> 00:17:13.973
Gold is only created
when stars die.

00:17:15.068 --> 00:17:16.527
That gives you the conditions
that can squeeze atoms together

00:17:17.609 --> 00:17:19.275
so hard to give you gold.

00:17:19.700 --> 00:17:20.683
So I said, if you want
to be romantic then

00:17:21.450 --> 00:17:25.316
you should say that a star had
to die to give us this ring.

00:17:27.119 --> 00:17:28.008
But we are implicitly tied
through that evolution

00:17:29.430 --> 00:17:29.440
of stars.

00:17:30.420 --> 00:17:32.426
There's no way we could have
had life in the early Universe

00:17:32.280 --> 00:17:33.031
with just hydrogen and helium.

00:17:33.529 --> 00:17:33.821
There's just not the
complexity there to have life.

00:17:36.570 --> 00:17:40.770
So what we have got of course is
we've got our picture of today.

00:17:42.090 --> 00:17:43.090
This is today.

00:17:43.154 --> 00:17:44.088
This is a lovely
picture taken in Chile.

00:17:44.820 --> 00:17:47.553
This is the VLT, the
Very Large Telescope.

00:17:48.370 --> 00:17:49.040
We are not very imaginative
in naming telescopes.

00:17:50.900 --> 00:17:50.956
The ELT is coming--

00:17:52.110 --> 00:17:53.843
Extremely Large Telescope.

00:17:53.880 --> 00:17:54.880
I kid you not.

00:17:55.510 --> 00:17:59.310
There's also OWL, which is
Overwhelmingly Large telescope.

00:18:00.454 --> 00:18:01.688
We should spend more time
when think of these names.

00:18:02.620 --> 00:18:02.750
But anyway, the VLT exists.

00:18:04.290 --> 00:18:04.380
It's in Chile.

00:18:05.200 --> 00:18:05.453
It's four 8-metre telescopes.

00:18:06.880 --> 00:18:07.713
All the good
telescopes in the world

00:18:08.380 --> 00:18:10.453
are now in Chile because they've
got some of the clearest skies

00:18:10.440 --> 00:18:10.703
and you can get up very high.

00:18:12.110 --> 00:18:13.433
And this is a beautiful view of
the centre of our own Milky Way

00:18:14.920 --> 00:18:15.920
galaxy.

00:18:16.630 --> 00:18:18.763
So if we were in
Chile, your eyes

00:18:19.110 --> 00:18:20.113
do not see quite as good
as this but the view

00:18:21.040 --> 00:18:22.440
is quite spectacular.

00:18:23.350 --> 00:18:23.903
But we find ourselves on
a rocky planet orbiting

00:18:25.930 --> 00:18:29.730
a fairly typical smallish star
in a reasonably big galaxy,

00:18:31.780 --> 00:18:34.446
which is one of many
hundreds of billions

00:18:34.960 --> 00:18:38.026
or trillions of other
galaxies in the Universe.

00:18:38.650 --> 00:18:40.783
Now, one of the
issues about when

00:18:42.160 --> 00:18:43.960
you think about evolution--

00:18:44.010 --> 00:18:46.743
let's go back to the
evolution of humans--

00:18:46.820 --> 00:18:47.121
is that we often
make the mistake,

00:18:48.719 --> 00:18:49.578
is that here we are,
here we are now,

00:18:50.260 --> 00:18:51.256
and therefore we are the
pinnacle of evolution.

00:18:52.330 --> 00:18:52.840
This must be the end point.

00:18:53.620 --> 00:18:54.093
How can it get better than this?

00:18:55.280 --> 00:18:56.280
Right?

00:18:56.467 --> 00:18:57.117
But of course we're wrong.

00:18:57.550 --> 00:18:58.000
Humans are still evolving,
still changing all the time.

00:19:00.700 --> 00:19:01.396
Evolution hasn't stopped
because we've suddenly

00:19:03.070 --> 00:19:04.536
discovered the iPhone.

00:19:05.050 --> 00:19:05.516
We are still evolving.

00:19:06.050 --> 00:19:06.808
And there are
different pressures

00:19:07.425 --> 00:19:10.491
on how things evolve but
we are still evolving.

00:19:10.600 --> 00:19:10.893
And it's the same
with the Universe.

00:19:12.640 --> 00:19:13.870
You might think, well, this
planet is quite comfortable

00:19:15.010 --> 00:19:15.693
and this Universe looks kind
of pretty and photogenic.

00:19:17.860 --> 00:19:18.860
Maybe this is the
pinnacle of the Universe.

00:19:19.660 --> 00:19:21.019
This is the way that it's
always going to be from now on.

00:19:22.034 --> 00:19:23.767
How can it get any better?

00:19:24.860 --> 00:19:25.016
Unfortunately, this is not
the pinnacle of the Universe.

00:19:28.370 --> 00:19:31.903
And at some level this is
the start of a long decline.

00:19:33.910 --> 00:19:34.336
So on that happy note, let's
now turn the picture around

00:19:37.150 --> 00:19:39.283
and start looking at the future.

00:19:40.690 --> 00:19:41.141
Now, in understanding the
future history of the Universe,

00:19:43.972 --> 00:19:44.780
we have some
limitations that we're

00:19:45.430 --> 00:19:47.363
going to have to acknowledge.

00:19:48.290 --> 00:19:48.973
Studying the Universe's
evolution from the Big Bang

00:19:50.940 --> 00:19:51.370
to now, you can have
a telescope and you

00:19:53.110 --> 00:19:53.963
can see what's happened
in the Universe

00:19:54.790 --> 00:19:57.790
to guide you in what
processes were important.

00:19:58.202 --> 00:19:59.310
But unfortunately, we
don't have any telescopes

00:20:00.160 --> 00:20:00.676
that can receive
light from the future.

00:20:02.177 --> 00:20:03.510
It would be beautiful to see
what the future Universe is

00:20:04.510 --> 00:20:05.663
going to do because that would
help you make a prediction

00:20:07.090 --> 00:20:08.623
because you can see it.

00:20:09.500 --> 00:20:10.000
So we don't.

00:20:10.000 --> 00:20:12.800
So at some level we're
working in the dark.

00:20:12.910 --> 00:20:13.303
We're going to make
predictions, and there

00:20:15.250 --> 00:20:15.433
will be some level
of uncertainty

00:20:17.200 --> 00:20:18.376
because we don't know everything
about our current state

00:20:19.690 --> 00:20:21.423
of the Universe perfectly.

00:20:21.634 --> 00:20:22.868
But there's a bigger problem,
and the bigger problem

00:20:23.800 --> 00:20:24.410
is that we don't know our
laws of physics perfectly.

00:20:26.590 --> 00:20:27.530
We know that we have some
very good laws of physics.

00:20:29.050 --> 00:20:30.783
We have quantum mechanics.

00:20:31.120 --> 00:20:32.540
If your iPhone wants to work,
it relies on quantum mechanics.

00:20:33.700 --> 00:20:36.766
We know that to a very
high degree of accuracy.

00:20:36.880 --> 00:20:37.410
We also have a really good
description of gravity

00:20:39.550 --> 00:20:39.640
given to us by Einstein.

00:20:41.060 --> 00:20:42.193
Again, GPS works.

00:20:42.580 --> 00:20:42.920
It gets you down to a centimetre
on the surface of the Earth.

00:20:46.240 --> 00:20:47.090
You need to worry about
Einstein's theory of gravity

00:20:48.790 --> 00:20:49.923
to make GPS work.

00:20:50.470 --> 00:20:51.440
The only problem that
we have is that, when

00:20:52.300 --> 00:20:53.530
we have conditions where we
have to worry about quantum

00:20:54.670 --> 00:20:54.743
mechanics and gravity
together, they just do not

00:20:57.730 --> 00:20:59.596
fit together mathematically.

00:21:00.010 --> 00:21:00.343
So there will be places
where we go into the future

00:21:03.010 --> 00:21:03.766
that this uncertainty of
how these sort of mesh

00:21:05.320 --> 00:21:07.720
together are going
to cause problems.

00:21:08.690 --> 00:21:09.203
So as we go out into
the far future Universe,

00:21:11.110 --> 00:21:11.203
we're going to get a
bit more speculative,

00:21:13.750 --> 00:21:17.150
and I'll try and flash a
speculation metre as we go.

00:21:17.230 --> 00:21:19.230
But nearby times, pretty good.

00:21:19.670 --> 00:21:23.470
Distant times, things are going
to get a little more ropy.

00:21:23.690 --> 00:21:24.611
So what's the first thing
that's going to happen?

00:21:25.969 --> 00:21:27.278
So what we're going to do is
we're going to go forward.

00:21:28.260 --> 00:21:28.826
And we'll go forward
in steps, but the steps

00:21:30.560 --> 00:21:33.293
will get bigger, because
the Universe will

00:21:33.320 --> 00:21:34.383
have different epochs
where things are important

00:21:35.390 --> 00:21:35.623
and they tend to be spaced out
at larger and larger steps.

00:21:38.957 --> 00:21:39.990
All we're going to worry
about at the moment

00:21:40.790 --> 00:21:42.856
are the next few billion years.

00:21:43.770 --> 00:21:44.956
So as was mentioned, Brexit
might be solved in that time

00:21:46.250 --> 00:21:47.716
scale or it might not.

00:21:48.080 --> 00:21:49.880
But what's going to happen?

00:21:50.550 --> 00:21:51.700
Well, the first thing that
we need to think about

00:21:52.600 --> 00:21:55.666
is essentially the end
of our Milky Way galaxy.

00:21:56.600 --> 00:21:56.680
Now, again, look at
that lovely picture.

00:21:59.120 --> 00:22:01.653
In a few billion
years it will be gone.

00:22:02.310 --> 00:22:03.510
So what do I mean?

00:22:03.900 --> 00:22:06.100
Well, here's our
Milky Way galaxy.

00:22:08.750 --> 00:22:09.089
It's a spiral galaxy.

00:22:09.811 --> 00:22:10.562
There's a bulge in the middle.

00:22:11.060 --> 00:22:11.566
Stars going around the outside.

00:22:12.620 --> 00:22:12.833
Our Sun is one of those
stars going around outside.

00:22:15.740 --> 00:22:16.093
The Sun takes 250 million
years to do one orbit around

00:22:18.920 --> 00:22:20.786
the centre of the Milky Way.

00:22:21.560 --> 00:22:22.420
The problem is the Milky Way
is not alone in the universe.

00:22:24.500 --> 00:22:25.196
It inhabits this
patch of the universe

00:22:26.270 --> 00:22:28.136
with two other big galaxies.

00:22:28.400 --> 00:22:31.000
One of them is called
M33 or Triangulum.

00:22:31.450 --> 00:22:32.263
It's a tenth the mass
of the Milky Way.

00:22:33.170 --> 00:22:34.170
We don't care.

00:22:34.680 --> 00:22:36.813
The other one,
M31, is Andromeda,

00:22:37.130 --> 00:22:37.430
which is about the same
size as the Milky Way.

00:22:39.830 --> 00:22:41.063
And Andromeda is approaching
us at half a million kilometres

00:22:42.530 --> 00:22:43.386
per hour, which, if we
do the maths quickly,

00:22:44.540 --> 00:22:47.940
which says in about 4 billion
years it will be here.

00:22:49.046 --> 00:22:50.405
So what's going to happen is
that Andromeda and the Milky

00:22:51.420 --> 00:22:53.086
Way are going to collide.

00:22:53.699 --> 00:22:54.858
So you saw there, that
was the initial collision.

00:22:55.740 --> 00:22:56.103
Stars started to get ripped off.

00:22:57.510 --> 00:23:01.310
So gravity pulls the stars,
starts to fling them outwards.

00:23:01.410 --> 00:23:02.393
Now, the Sun might be
one of those stars that

00:23:03.360 --> 00:23:06.560
ends up being thrown out
of the Milky Way galaxy.

00:23:07.694 --> 00:23:08.478
So the collision
is just starting.

00:23:09.110 --> 00:23:10.068
Now, before I proceed,
I should point out

00:23:10.818 --> 00:23:11.472
I've got a little
time scale up there,

00:23:12.630 --> 00:23:15.896
and I've tried to use words
to describe the times.

00:23:16.670 --> 00:23:17.470
So a billion years,
that makes sense.

00:23:18.270 --> 00:23:18.980
We all know what a billion is.

